/b> CT scan shows diffuse, irregular thickening of the jejunal loop (circled), a finding that corresponds to the tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.253045134&amp;id=F8D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.253045134/asset/images/g05ma10c9x.jpeg" height="1227" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9.</b>  Carcinoid tumor. Capsule endoscopic image shows a carcinoid tumor measuring 1.7 cm in diameter that was not detected at barium examination or CT. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#R2" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="R2">2</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.253045134&amp;id=F9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.253045134/asset/images/g05ma10c10a.jpeg" height="1280" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F10A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10a.</b>  Lymphoma. <b>(a)</b> Capsule endoscopic image shows small nodules in the jejunum. <b>(b)</b> EGD image demonstrates an irregular lobulated mass. <b>(c)</b> Image from a small bowel follow-through study demonstrates an abnormal jejunal small bowel loop (circled). The examination was initially thought to be negative. <b>(d)</b> CT scan shows eccentric irregular thickening of the jejunal loop (circled), a finding that represents lymphoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.253045134&amp;id=F10A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.253045134/asset/images/g05ma10c10b.jpeg" height="1280" width="1210" aria-labelledby="F10B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10b.</b>  Lymphoma. <b>(a)</b> Capsule endoscopic image shows small nodules in the jejunum. <b>(b)</b> EGD image demonstrates an irregular lobulated mass. <b>(c)</b> Image from a small bowel follow-through study demonstrates an abnormal jejunal small bowel loop (circled). The examination was initially thought to be negative. <b>(d)</b> CT scan shows eccentric irregular thickening of the jejunal loop (circled), a finding that represents lymphoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.253045134&amp;id=F10B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.253045134/asset/images/g05ma10g10c.jpeg" height="1671" width="1692" aria-labelledby="F10C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10c.</b>  Lymphoma. <b>(a)</b> Capsule endoscopic image shows small nodules in the jejunum. <b>(b)</b> EGD image demonstrates an irregular lobulated mass. <b>(c)</b> Image from a small bowel follow-through study demonstrates an abnormal jejunal small bowel loop (circled). The examination was initially thought to be negative. <b>(d)</b> CT scan shows eccentric irregular thickening of the jejunal loop (circled), a finding that represents lymphoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.253045134&amp;id=F10C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.253045134/asset/images/g05ma10g10d.jpeg" height="1776" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10d.</b>  Lymphoma. <b>(a)</b> Capsule endoscopic image shows small nodules in the jejunum. <b>(b)</b> EGD image demonstrates an irregular lobulated mass. <b>(c)</b> Image from a small bowel follow-through study demonstrates an abnormal jejunal small bowel loop (circled). The examination was initially thought to be negative. <b>(d)</b> CT scan shows eccentric irregular thickening of the jejunal loop (circled), a finding that represents lymphoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.253045134&amp;id=F10D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.253045134/asset/images/g05ma10c11a.jpeg" height="1280" width="1278" aria-labelledby="F11A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11a.</b>  Ovarian cancer invading the terminal ileum. <b>(a)</b> Capsule endoscopic image shows a small bowel stricture of unknown origin (arrows) causing obstruction of the capsule. <b>(b)</b> CT scan shows the capsule (circled) in the distal ileum. <b>(c)</b> CT scan shows a large, heterogeneous mass (arrow) invading the terminal ileum and causing a small bowel stricture. <b>(d)</b> CT scan shows the invasive mass arising from the right ovary.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.253045134&amp;id=F11A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.253045134/asset/images/g05ma10g11b.jpeg" height="1530" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F11B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11b.</b>  Ovarian cancer invading the terminal ileum. <b>(a)</b> Capsule endoscopic image shows a small bowel stricture of unknown origin (arrows) causing obstruction of the capsule. <b>(b)</b> CT scan shows the capsule (circled) in the distal ileum. <b>(c)</b> CT scan shows a large, heterogeneous mass (arrow) invading the terminal ileum and causing a small bowel stricture. <b>(d)</b> CT scan shows the invasive mass arising from the right ovary.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.253045134&amp;id=F11B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.253045134/asset/images/g05ma10g11c.jpeg" height="1607" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F11C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11c.</b>  Ovarian cancer invading the terminal ileum. <b>(a)</b> Capsule endoscopic image shows a small bowel stricture of unknown origin (arrows) causing obstruction of the capsule. <b>(b)</b> CT scan shows the capsule (circled) in the distal ileum. <b>(c)</b> CT scan shows a large, heterogeneous mass (arrow) invading the terminal ileum and causing a small bowel stricture. <b>(d)</b> CT scan shows the invasive mass arising from the right ovary.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.253045134&amp;id=F11C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.253045134/asset/images/g05ma10g11d.jpeg" height="1643" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F11D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11d.</b>  Ovarian cancer invading the terminal ileum. <b>(a)</b> Capsule endoscopic image shows a small bowel stricture of unknown origin (arrows) causing obstruction of the capsule. <b>(b)</b> CT scan shows the capsule (circled) in the distal ileum. <b>(c)</b> CT scan shows a large, heterogeneous mass (arrow) invading the terminal ileum and causing a small bowel stricture. <b>(d)</b> CT scan shows the invasive mass arising from the right ovary.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.253045134&amp;id=F11D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.253045134/asset/images/g05ma10c12x.jpeg" height="1197" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12.</b>  Small bowel ulcers. Capsule endoscopic image shows small bowel ulcers that were not seen at enteroclysis or CT.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.253045134&amp;id=F12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.253045134/asset/images/g05ma10g13a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1798" aria-labelledby="F13A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13a.</b>  Early Crohn disease. <b>(a)</b> Image from a small bowel follow-through study shows mild nodularity in the terminal ileum (arrows). <b>(b)</b> CT scan shows mild diffuse wall thickening and mucosal enhancement of the terminal ileum (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Capsule endoscopic image shows a small apthous ulcer in the terminal ileum (circled).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.253045134&amp;id=F13A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.253045134/asset/images/g05ma10g13b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1548" aria-labelledby="F13B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13b.</b>  Early Crohn disease. <b>(a)</b> Image from a small bowel follow-through study shows mild nodularity in the terminal ileum (arrows). <b>(b)</b> CT scan shows mild diffuse wall thickening and mucosal enhancement of the terminal ileum (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Capsule endoscopic image shows a small apthous ulcer in the terminal ileum (circled).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.253045134&amp;id=F13B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.253045134/asset/images/g05ma10c13c.jpeg" height="1199" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F13C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13c.</b>  Early Crohn disease. <b>(a)</b> Image from a small bowel follow-through study shows mild nodularity in the terminal ileum (arrows). <b>(b)</b> CT scan shows mild diffuse wall thickening and mucosal enhancement of the terminal ileum (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Capsule endoscopic image shows a small apthous ulcer in the terminal ileum (circled).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.253045134&amp;id=F13C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.253045134/asset/images/g05ma10g14a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1778" aria-labelledby="F14A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14a.</b>  Early Crohn disease in another patient. <b>(a)</b> Image from a small bowel follow-through study shows mild nodularity in the terminal ileum (arrow). <b>(b)</b> CT scan shows mild diffuse wall thickening and markedly increased mucosal enhancement of the terminal ileum (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Capsule endoscopic image shows a small apthous ulcer in the terminal ileum (circled).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.253045134&amp;id=F14A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.253045134/asset/images/g05ma10g14b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1506" aria